
  <sn><md>## **Title: Determination of clay mineral type using CEC method**

### **Definition:**
Cation exchange capacity is the amount of exchangeable cations present in soil, which are held on the surface of soil particles at pH 7.

These cations include:
$Ca^{2+}$, $Mg^{2+}$, $Na^{+}$, $K^{+}$, $H^{+}$, $Al^{3+}$

So $CEC = Ca^{2+} + Mg^{2+} + Na^{+} + K^{+} + H^{+} + Al^{3+}$

---

### **Principle:**
The cation exchange capacity is usually measured by leaching the soil with an excess of $1N$ ammonium acetate solution at a neutral pH value and then washing out the excess salts with an alcohol. The amount of cations ($NH_4^+$) retained by soil after washing is the measure of CEC in soil.

---

### **Apparatus:**
1. 250 mL conical flask
2. Funnel, filter paper (Whatman no. 42)
3. 250 mL volumetric flask
4. Distillation apparatus and other requirements which are used in alkali distillation on nitrogen determination.

---

### **Reagents:**
1. **Ammonium Acetate ($NH_4OAc$):**
2. **95% Ethyl alcohol**
3. **$1N$ Sodium chloride:** (Dissolve $58.5g$ NaCl in $1L$ volumetric flask and adjust pH to pH 7 with NaOH).

---

### **Procedure:**
1. At first we collected soil from the central field.
2. Then we measured $10g$ of soil using weighing balance.
3. Transfer $10g$ of soil in $250 \text{ mL}$ conical flask.
4. Then prepare $1N$ $NH_4OAc$ solution by mixing $57 \text{ mL}$ acetic acid and $69 \text{ mL}$ ammonium hydroxide in about $900 \text{ mL}$ water to get neutral pH and add more water to get the volume of 1 liter. 
5. Add $100 \text{ mL}$ $1N$ $NH_4OAc$ solution in the conical flask.
6. Shake the mixture and leave it to stand overnight.
7. Filter the mixture through filter paper and transfer the filtrate in $250 \text{ mL}$ volumetric flask.
8. Wash the residue on the filter paper 5 times using ethyl alcohol. Take $10 \text{ mL}$ each time and discard the filtrate.
9. Then wash the soil residue on the filter paper with neutral $1N$ NaCl solution 4 times. Collect the filtrate (solution) in $250 \text{ mL}$ volumetric flask and make the final volume up to the mark with NaCl solution.
10. **Alkali distillation:** Take $10 \text{ mL}$ of solution, add $10 \text{ mL}$ NaOH and add $100 \text{ mL}$ distilled water and put it in the distillation machine.
11. Collect $60 \text{ mL}$ of distillate in a conical flask and $10 \text{ mL}$ boric acid is added to it.
12. Take standard $H_2SO_4$ solution in a burette and titrate the distillate (add it to the conical flask) until the blue colour of the solution is changed to orange colour and indicate the end point.
13. Run a blank experiment simultaneously using all the chemicals except soil.

---

### **Data Table:**

| No. | IBR | FBR | Diff | Mean |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Soil Sample 01** | 0 | 3.1 | 3.1 | 3.1 |
| **Soil Sample 02** | 3.1 | 6.2 | 3.1 | |
| **Blank 01** | 0 | 0.14 | 0.14 | 0.14 |
| **Blank 02** | 0.14 | 0.28 | 0.14 | |

---

### **Calculation:**

$$\%N \text{ in soil} = \frac{14 \times 0.018 \times 250 \times 100}{1000 \times 10 \times 10} \times (T-B)$$

$$= 0.063 \times (3.1 - 0.14)$$
$$= 0.1865$$

$$\therefore \text{CEC in soil} = \frac{0.1865 \times 1000}{14} = 13.32$$</md></sn>
